The paper discusses a reasoning system that involves defaults, likelihood, necessity, and possibility, which are all concepts related to artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The system is based on the belief calculus of subjective Bayesian probability, which is a common topic in machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also touches on issues of consistency and consequence, which are relevant to logic (cs.LO) and computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the paper discusses the approximate nature of plausible reasoning, which is a topic in cryptography (cs.CR) where probabilistic reasoning is often used.
